We can see there was always a peak in months June to September. In my guess, it's summertime between June and September, so the higher electricity consumption might because of the more usage of airconditioner. And the CPI for electricity is also a slightly higher in November and December, I guess this is because of the more heating needs during winter time.

1. Exponantial Smoothing Model¶


We can see the residuals are more volatile in the early and later years, a roughly increasing error in recent years as compared with years between 1985 and 2001. There's also an upward approximately linear trend and a constant seasonal component as well. Therefore, I'm going to use the Holt-Winter's Seasonal Smoothing Model. One model doesn't have damping factor, the second one has damping factor.

In [22]:
model1=ExponentialSmoothing(train,trend="add",seasonal="add",seasonal_periods=12)
model2=ExponentialSmoothing(train,trend="add",seasonal="add",seasonal_periods=12,damped=True)

fit1=model1.fit()
pred1=fit1.forecast(test.shape[0])
fit2=model2.fit()
pred2=fit2.forecast(test.shape[0])

sse1 = np.sqrt(np.mean(np.square(test.values - pred1.values)))
sse2 = np.sqrt(np.mean(np.square(test.values - pred2.values)))

2. Seasonal ARIMA Model¶


As we discovered a constant seasonal pattern above, I need to make the time series stationary.

In [40]:
# Define a function for checking the stationarity of the series.
# These codes can be found at https://www.seanabu.com/2016/03/22/time-series-seasonal-ARIMA-model-in-python/
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import adfuller
def test_stationarity(timeseries):

    #Determing rolling statistics
    rolmean = timeseries.rolling(window=12).mean()
    rolstd = timeseries.rolling(window=12).std()

    #Plot rolling statistics:
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))
    orig = plt.plot(timeseries, color='blue',label='Original')
    mean = plt.plot(rolmean, color='red', label='Rolling Mean')
    std = plt.plot(rolstd, color='black', label = 'Rolling Std')
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.title('Rolling Mean & Standard Deviation')
    plt.xlabel("Year");
    plt.ylabel("Index");
    plt.show()
    
    #Perform Dickey-Fuller test:
    print('Results of Dickey-Fuller Test:')
    dftest = adfuller(timeseries, autolag='AIC')
    dfoutput = pd.Series(dftest[0:4], index=['Test Statistic','p-value','#Lags Used','Number of Observations Used'])
    for key,value in dftest[4].items():
        dfoutput['Critical Value (%s)'%key] = value
    print(dfoutput)

D and d parameters should all be 1, the positive lag 1 in both autocorrelation and partial autocorrelation plot also confirmed that p should be 1, and there's a significant lag at the first season at 12 in both acf and pacf plots, so Q is 1 as well. So the ARIMA model should be ARIMA(1,1,0)x(0,1,1,12).

  • Measures of Error
In [63]:
#Calculate the MAE, MSE, MAPE, MPE, ME, RMSE for the three model.
MAE=[]
MSE=[]
MAPE=[]
MPE=[]
ME=[]
RMSE=[]

for i,p in zip(range(5),[pred1,pred2,df_sub["forecast"]]):
    mae_sum=(y_test-p).sum()
    mae=mae_sum/len(y_test)
    mse_sum=((y_test-p)**2).sum()
    mse=mse_sum/len(y_test)
    mape_sum=((abs(y_test-p))/y_test).sum()
    mape=mape_sum/len(y_test)
    mpe_sum=((y_test-p)/y_test).sum()
    mpe=mpe_sum/len(y_test)
    me_sum=(y_test-p).sum()
    me=me_sum/len(y_test)
    rsme=np.sqrt(((y_test-p)**2).sum()/len(y_test))
    MAE.append(mae)
    MSE.append(mse)
    MAPE.append(mape)
    MPE.append(mpe)
    ME.append(me)
    RMSE.append(rsme)
